    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my checkride and i'm a bit confused about pitot tubes. can u explain how they actually work to measure airspeed? specifically how the pressure difference creates the reading?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! Pitot tubes measure airspeed by comparing static and total pressure. Static air (unchanged air around the airplane) exerts a lower pressure, while the air flowing into the pitot tube (total pressure) is higher. The pressure difference between the two readings (total minus static) equals the dynamic pressure, which, when combined with air density and velocity, allows us to calculate the airspeed using Bernoulli's equation. The difference reveals the relative speed of the aircraft against the ambient air.",
      "source": "target",
