    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i get that. but i was reading that bugs or small debris can get in there. is it common for something that small to completely mess up the reading? i'm just trying to visualize how something so tiny can have such a huge impact on the flight instruments.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube's function relies on accurate pressure differences. Even a small obstruction, like a bug, can increase the static pressure, which reduces the difference between total and static pressure, thus lowering the reading on the airspeed indicator. While it's not common, it is possible for small debris to have a noticeable impact on airspeed readings. The effect could be either an overestimation or underestimation of the airspeed. That's why aircrews inspect pitot tubes meticulously before each flight to ensure they function properly. Rigorous inspections following the discovery of insects in the tube help mitigate the risk of inaccurate readings.",
      "source": "target",
